{"title":"Using Local Experiences for Global Motion Planning","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Sampling-based motion planners often fail or become inefficient in environments with narrow passages because uninformed or heuristic sampling rarely hits critical C-space regions; learned workspace-to-configuration mappings may not reliably place samples in those regions.","method":"Decompose the workspace into local primitives (e.g., pairs of obstacles) and, for each primitive, solve targeted local motion-planning queries multiple times to harvest configurations that traverse difficult regions. Fit a local sampler per primitive as a Gaussian Mixture Model by placing one mixture per harvested configuration with a fixed covariance (no EM), then optionally reduce mixtures by merging cliques of straight-line-connected configurations to respect C-space connectivity. Store each primitive’s sampler parameters in a database for reuse."},{"problem":"To transfer prior experience and guide planning in a new environment, we need to efficiently adapt stored local knowledge to the current workspace and compose it into an effective global sampling distribution.","method":"Given a new workspace, decompose it into local primitives and retrieve matching local samplers from the database using a similarity function (negative squared Euclidean distance) with a threshold; if no close match exists, compute and insert a new local sampler. Synthesize a global sampler by mixing the retrieved local samplers via a law-of-total-probability-based approximation, weighting each local sampler proportionally to its number of mixtures (a_i = M_i/N), and use this GL-Sampler alongside uniform sampling within standard planners (PRM/RRT/BiRRT)."},{"problem":"A naive database of many local samplers can be large and slow to query online, and similar primitives across symmetric variants cause redundancy.","method":"Reduce database size and redundancy by (i) merging cliques: build a graph over harvested configurations and greedily merge fully connected subgraphs into single GMM components; and (ii) exploiting robot symmetries to transform samplers across primitives (e.g., rotational invariance: rotate the primitive and shift the first joint’s GMM means by θ), effectively lowering the descriptor dimensionality and enabling millisecond-level retrieval in experiments."}]}
